parameter name 'turn' everywhere and removing legacy/unused code.

Changes:

- IAgentClient interface: Unified to 'turn' parameter

- Smaller, clearer codebase with no compatibility shims
- All 110 tests passing

issue.title: fix: handle locals() calls in wrapped modules by static analysis
issue.body:
## Summary

This PR fixes bundling of modules that use `locals()` to dynamically access imported symbols, a pattern used by libraries like httpx to set `__module__` attributes.

## Changes

- **Static analysis for `locals()` calls**: When a module-level `locals()` call is detected, it's replaced with a statically determined dictionary containing all module-level symbols
- **`__all__` reference detection**: Added detection for when `__all__` variable is referenced elsewhere in the module (e.g., in loops), ensuring it's preserved when needed
- **AST builder enhancement**: Added `dict()` and `dict_item()` helper functions to the ast_builder for cleaner dictionary construction
- **Test fixture**: Added test case based on httpx's pattern of using `locals()` to access imported symbols

## Problem & Solution

The issue occurred when bundling modules that use this pattern:
```python
from ._internal import MyClass, my_func
__all__ = ["MyClass", "my_func"]
__locals = locals()  # Capture module-level locals
for __name in __all__:
    setattr(__locals[__name], "__module__", "mypkg")
```

In the bundled wrapper function, `locals()` returns function-local variables, not the imported symbols which are now global. The solution uses static analysis to determine what `locals()` would return at module level and replaces it with a dictionary literal containing the correct symbols.

## Test Results

- âœ… All existing tests pass
- âœ… New test fixture for the httpx pattern works correctly
- âœ… Clippy validation passes (only unused `dict_item` warning, kept for future use)

- New Features
  - Wrapper modules now initialize once, are ordered by dependencies, and wire imports immediately during wrapper initialization.
  - Added a per-statement utility to detect whether a statement references a given variable.

- Bug Fixes
  - locals()/globals() introspection reliably rewired to the module namespace; __all__ is propagated only when actually referenced.
  - Import aliasing and inlined export wiring improved for correct availability.

- Refactor
  - Centralized module-namespace handling behind a single canonical module-namespace variable and unified introspection transformation.

comment.body:
The nullish coalescing operator `??` is redundant here since you're already checking `values.other` in the ternary condition. If `values.other` is truthy, it won't be null or undefined, making the fallback to "others" unreachable.
```suggestion
                    values.other ? `: ${values.other}` : ""
```

### Device model name

Dockstream 2 Smart Fountain (Cordless)

### Device model number

PLWF116

### Device type

Fountain

### What state, statistic or control do you want to be reported in the integration ?

Current water level with ability to set the reminder level
Battery level left if in cordless mode.
Filter time remaining
Time until cleaning needed
Drink logs with amount consumed
How many daily visits
Average duration
Goal
measurement unit 
Access to indicator lights
Firmware Version and if update is available
Water flow type and ability to select which type 
This fountain has the feature to select the flow type as pet sensing and there are two options with sensing, Near the device and far trigger. It would be nice to be able to set this as well. Also, the ability to maybe expose the sensor as a motion sensor for other automations. 

I know I included a lot, but I figured I would try to capture as much as I could. Once again, thank you for this project. 

### Available to help integrate the new device

- [x] I agree to help with the integration of the new device by providing the necessary information that will be requested

comment.body: @trentsmart, its going well so far, ive got the selector working for the water dispensing mode and quite a few sensors. to implement a sensor that shows if its plugged in/is charging or using battery, please can you ping me when you happen to plug it in please? i can then see what `powerMode`, `powerType`, and `powerState` are updated to, as i bet that these are what control most of it. screenshots of what i have so far:

pull_request.title: chore(deps): bump react-dom and @types/react-dom
pull_request.body:
Bumps [react-dom](https://github.com/facebook/react/tree/HEAD/packages/react-dom) and [@types/react-dom](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/HEAD/types/react-dom). These dependencies needed to be updated together. Updates `react-dom` from 18.3.1 to 19.1.1
Release notes

Sourced from react-dom's releases.

19.1.1 (July 28, 2025)

React

  • Fixed Owner Stacks to work with ES2015 function.name semantics (#33680 by @â€‹hoxyq)

19.1.0 (March 28, 2025)

Owner Stack

An Owner Stack is a string representing the components that are directly responsible for rendering a particular component. You can log Owner Stacks when debugging or use Owner Stacks to enhance error overlays or other development tools. Owner Stacks are only available in development builds. Component Stacks in production are unchanged.

  • An Owner Stack is a development-only stack trace that helps identify which components are responsible for rendering a particular component. An Owner Stack is distinct from a Component Stacks, which shows the hierarchy of components leading to an error.
  • The captureOwnerStack API is only available in development mode and returns a Owner Stack, if available. The API can be used to enhance error overlays or log component relationships when debugging. #29923, #32353, #30306, #32538, #32529, #32538

React

  • Enhanced support for Suspense boundaries to be used anywhere, including the client, server, and during hydration. #32069, #32163, #32224, #32252
  • Reduced unnecessary client rendering through improved hydration scheduling #31751
  • Increased priority of client rendered Suspense boundaries #31776
  • Fixed frozen fallback states by rendering unfinished Suspense boundaries on the client. #31620
  • Reduced garbage collection pressure by improving Suspense boundary retries. #31667
  • Fixed erroneous â€œWaiting for Paintâ€ log when the passive effect phase was not delayed #31526
  • Fixed a regression causing key warnings for flattened positional children in development mode. #32117
  • Updated useId to use valid CSS selectors, changing format from :r123: to Â«r123Â». #32001
  • Added a dev-only warning for null/undefined created in useEffect, useInsertionEffect, and useLayoutEffect. #32355
  • Fixed a bug where dev-only methods were exported in production builds. React.act is no longer available in production builds. #32200
  • Improved consistency across prod and dev to improve compatibility with Google Closure Complier and bindings #31808
  • Improve passive effect scheduling for consistent task yielding. #31785
  • Fixed asserts in React Native when passChildrenWhenCloningPersistedNodes is enabled for OffscreenComponent rendering. #32528
  • Fixed component name resolution for Portal #32640
  • Added support for beforetoggle and toggle events on the dialog element. #32479 #32479

React DOM

  • Fixed double warning when the href attribute is an empty string #31783
  • Fixed an edge case where getHoistableRoot() didnâ€™t work properly when the container was a Document #32321
  • Removed support for using HTML comments (e.g. <!-- -->) as a DOM container. #32250
  • Added support for <script> and \<template> tags to be nested within <select> tags. #31837
  • Fixed responsive images to be preloaded as HTML instead of headers #32445

use-sync-external-store

  • Added exports field to package.json for use-sync-external-store to support various entrypoints. #25231

React Server Components

  • Added unstable_prerender, a new experimental API for prerendering React Server Components on the server #31724
  • Fixed an issue where streams would hang when receiving new chunks after a global error #31840, #31851
  • Fixed an issue where pending chunks were counted twice. #31833
  • Added support for streaming in edge environments #31852
  • Added support for sending custom error names from a server so that they are available in the client for console replaying. #32116
  • Updated the server component wire format to remove IDs for hints and console.log because they have no return value #31671
  • Exposed registerServerReference in client builds to handle server references in different environments. #32534
  • Added react-server-dom-parcel package which integrates Server Components with the Parcel bundler #31725, #32132, #31799, #32294, #31741

... (truncated)

commits.message:
Enhanced ApiResponse DTO and created supporting Message/Enum classes for COBOL migration

- Updated ApiResponse.java to fix enum organization issues for Java compliance
- Created MessageLevel.java enum with INFO, WARNING, ERROR levels mapping to BMS color coding
- Created ResponseStatus.java enum with SUCCESS, ERROR states for CICS transaction equivalents
- Created comprehensive Message.java DTO with MessageLevel support and field-level validation
- All DTOs follow COBOL-to-Java migration patterns for CICS transaction processing
- Supports generic response wrapper with status tracking, messages list, and session updates
- Maps CICS COMMAREA functionality through sessionUpdates for session management
- Maintains functional parity with mainframe BMS message handling patterns
- All 11 comprehensive unit tests pass (100% success rate)
- Zero compilation errors, all classes compile successfully with Java 21
- Full Spring Boot 3.x integration support with Jackson annotations

issue.title: Getting real card parameters and using them in Javascript Templates
issue.body:
Hello. 
In the case when some card parameters are set as a percentage (for example, the width or height of the card), the actual parameters will vary depending on the device parameters (in particular, the display resolution) and the browser used. 
For example, there may be a situation in which the card will have a larger width (in pixels) on one device, and a smaller one on the other. But the width of a text box containing, for example, the name of an entity will be the same in both cases. 
Let's say the width of this text box is less than the width of the card on the first device, but it is larger than the width of the card on the second device.
Respectively, on the first device the entity name will be displayed in full, but not on the second. 
I would like to be able (in the case described above) to get the real width of the card on the device and the real width of the text box containing the name of the entity, be able to compare them, and also use the comparison result in Javascript Templates.
For example, for the second case, it would be possible to assign word wrapping to a new line, reduce the font size, or arrange automatic horizontal scrolling of the text. But the most important thing is that all these additional activities should only take place when the width of the text box is larger than the width of the card. That is, for example, I do not need automatic horizontal scrolling of the text or font size reduction in the event that it already fits completely on the card.
To organize what I described above, I apparently need to get the real width values inside Javascript Templates. 
More generally, access to more card parameters (as well as its composite and nested elements) inside Javascript Templates is desirable. 
Is there even such a possibility? Or maybe it can be provided in future versions?

comment.body:
@dcapslock,
> then think about reflowing the buttons so that they stack rather than quish

As far as I understand, the Home Assistant dashboards themselves, in accordance with some specific rules, determine the number of columns for placing cards, depending on the available width. Apparently, we have a more "flexible" situation when using the Sections layout, but there are still some rules that may change the number of columns when the available width is reached... To be honest, I don't really like the idea of moving the buttons to a new row (in some situations, it may disrupt the logic of their placement based on their functionality), and it's not always possible... So, as far as I understand, I can only provide for the use of the "scroll" described above in cases where the width of the cards decreases when the dashboard's content is "rebuilt" in case of available width - and using css, this works perfectly in all situations!
> Without knowing your whole config its hard to provide an example.

I don't have this configuration anymore either, as the css works perfectly when the sidebar's state changes... My question was about how this could help in a situation where the css is not being used (my initial solution). However, it now has only theoretical significance, as there is an easier and more effective solution available... 
> Overall, think about how CSS provides for what you need, not a state machine that you need to track.

Thank you so much for your help and clarification, and I will try to delve deeper into the possibilities provided by css whenever possible!

- Copilot Chat Extension Version: 0.30.1
- VS Code Version: 1.103.1 (Universal)
- OS Version: MacOS 10.5
- Feature (e.g. agent/edit/ask mode): None
- Selected model (e.g. GPT 4.1, Claude 3.7 Sonnet): Claude 4.0 Sonnet, GPT 5
- Logs:

```
"code_scanning_upload": {
    "limit": 5000,
    "used": 1029,
    "remaining": 3971,
    "reset": 1755443661
},
```

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Open vscode with any code folder.
2. Enable Copilot extension.
3. Check the rate limit from `https://api.github.com/rate_limit` 
4. It fires 10 code scanning update request per second in an idle vscode instance.
5. The requests didn't shown in vscode dev tool console or network tab.
6. This quickly exhaust the GitHub API 5000 requests per hour limit if I open multiple projects.
7.  This dramatically affect my work, cannot interact with GitHub just 10-15 mins after the limit reset.

issue.title: Issues trying to do supabase start, supabase pull and other commands locally
issue.body:
I've been unable to do supabase start or supabase pull of my project, failing with docker issues. The core issue seems to stem from this:

```
This is the acutal error I get WARNING:  invalid configuration parameter name "supautils.extension_custom_scripts_path", removing it
DETAIL:  "supautils" is now a reserved prefix.
psql: error: /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/init-scripts/99-roles.sql: No such file or directory
[directory] container is not ready: unhealthy
```

The crash report id is `c0a5e6cc8e61429989ec501b82c01786`

I've not foudn the way to modify "supautils.extension_custom_scripts_path" or similar in the remote instance.

comment.body:
Temporary fix I have gotten so far.
find out the name of your container for postgres using 
`docker ps`

Then connect to it. (mine was supabase_db_ekko)
`docker exec -it supabase_db_ekko sh`

You will now have a terminal inside the postgres container. take a look at the config. 
`cat /etc/postgresql-custom/supautils.conf`

You will see the problematic line
supautils.extension_custom_scripts_path = '/etc/postgresql-custom/extension-custom-scripts'
That is what we wanna delete. 

I counted mine to be on line 10, so i deleted it using "sed" . since theres no nano or vim in the container, you can find your own way to edit the file to delete that line. 
`sed -i '10d' /etc/postgresql-custom/supautils.conf`

That command deleted line 10 from the file. 
I then reset my local supabase db

`supabase db reset`

Error is gone for now, it will return if I run supabase stop.

Creating a QApplication instance automatically in a component module can cause issues in testing and application lifecycle management. This should be handled by the main application entry point.

```suggestion
# NOTE: Requires a QApplication to be created before using QWidget-based classes.

```

Using QTimer.start(0) in a loop can cause excessive CPU usage as it triggers on every event loop iteration. Consider using a minimum delay (e.g., 10ms) to allow other operations to process.
```suggestion
            # Use a small non-zero delay to avoid excessive CPU usage
            self._batch_timer.start(10)
```

Converting QMessageBox reply to string and checking for 'Yes' is fragile. The original comparison 'reply == QMessageBox.StandardButton.Yes' should be sufficient and more reliable.
```suggestion
        if reply == QMessageBox.StandardButton.Yes:
```

issue.title: Critical: Trigram index panics on Unicode content during string slicing
issue.body:
## ðŸ› Bug Report

### Description
The trigram index crashes with a panic when processing Unicode content due to unsafe string slicing at byte boundaries that don't respect UTF-8 character boundaries.

### Error Details
```
thread 'main' panicked at src/trigram_index.rs:653:46:
byte index 497 is not a char boundary; it is inside 'ä¸­' (bytes 496..499)
```

### Location
File: `src/trigram_index.rs:653`
Code: `format!("{} ...", &content_str[..497])`

### Root Cause
The code attempts to slice a string at a fixed byte position (497) for creating a content preview, but this position may fall in the middle of a multi-byte UTF-8 character. When the content contains Unicode characters like Chinese text 'ä¸­', the slice operation panics.

### Impact
- **Severity**: CRITICAL - Causes complete application crash
- **Affected Operations**: 
  - Git repository ingestion fails
  - Any document insertion with Unicode content fails
  - Database becomes unusable for international content

### Reproduction Steps
1. Create a document with Unicode content (Chinese, emoji, etc.)
2. Try to insert it into KotaDB
3. Application panics at trigram index insertion

### Discovery Method
Found during dogfooding validation while ingesting KotaDB's own codebase, which contains Unicode test files (`tests/unicode_handling_test.rs`).

### Suggested Fix
Use proper UTF-8 aware string slicing:
```rust
// Instead of:
format!("{} ...", &content_str[..497])

// Use char_indices to find safe boundary:
let truncate_at = content_str.char_indices()
    .take(497)  // Take first 497 chars
    .last()
    .map(|(i, _)| i)
    .unwrap_or(content_str.len());
format!("{} ...", &content_str[..truncate_at])
```

### Related
- `tests/unicode_handling_test.rs` - Contains Unicode test cases that trigger this bug
- Issue #106 mentioned in the test file about Unicode handling

### Priority
This is a **CRITICAL** bug that completely breaks Unicode support and makes KotaDB unusable for international content.

### Validation Note
This issue was discovered through continuous dogfooding validation (Issue #214), demonstrating the value of testing KotaDB on its own codebase.

The changes implement static import cycle detection, service layer patterns, and improved import management across the GUI, tools, and database layers.
